{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}
[[File:Wroxham_Broad_capsize_practise.JPG|thumb|right|Practice righting a capsized dinghy]] 
In [[dinghy]] [[sailing]], a boat is said to be '''turtling''' or to '''turn turtle''' when the boat is fully inverted with the mast pointing down to the lake bottom or seabed.  The name stems from the appearance of the upside-down boat, similar to the shell of a [[sea turtle]]. The term can be applied to any vessel; turning turtle is less frequent but more dangerous on ships than on smaller boats.  It is more hazardous on multihulls.  Measures can be taken to prevent a capsize from becoming a turtle.{{sfn|George|1971|p=82-9}}

==Definition and prevention==
Prevention is the first priority.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/><ref name="f15"/> <ref group=upper-alpha>"A seaman laboring under an undue sense of security becomes at once worth hardly half his salt." {{ndash}} [[Joseph Conrad]]. {{cite book |first1=Joseph |last1=Conrad |authorlink1=Joseph Conrad |title=The Mirror of the Sea |page=18 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=t3hJAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22A+seaman+laboring+under+an+undue+sense+of+security+becomes+at+once+worth+hardly+half+his+salt.%22&source=bl&ots=L2dGyVXWWx&sig=NNmcg7TGONfyAbMpyMqQKFmTVig&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YiaOUrLdIKPSyAG05ICwBA&ved=0CDAQ6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=%22A%20seaman%20laboring%20under%20an%20undue%20sense%20of%20security%20becomes%20at%20once%20worth%20hardly%20half%20his%20salt.%22&f=false |accessdate=November 21, 2013}} cited in Rosmaniere at p. 19.</ref>

Turtling commonly occurs when a boat [[capsize]]s and is not righted or attended to in time, allowing it to roll through the approximately 90 degrees of a capsize through to 180 degrees from upright.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/><ref name="f15"/>

Prevention and delay of turtling in dinghies is the highest priority {{mdash}} turtling can be catastrophic in consequences {{mdash}} but it depends on skill, ability and athleticism, which vary greatly.  As [[John Rousmaniere]] wrote: Testing confirms the [[Royal Yachting Association]]'s conclusion that "a decisive way to address entrapment is to immediately right the boat by putting weight on the centerboad."<ref name="Rosmaniere"/> This should be adopted by [[US Sailing]] and other organizations "as doctrine."<ref name="Rosmaniere"/> Thus, reliance on boat handling and [[seamanship]] may be misplaced.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/>  

Sealing masts and attaching flotation are effective preventatives, but not widely utilized.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/><ref name="f15"/>  More certain preventatives for this includes various forms of flotation added to the tip of the mast or top of the mainsail.<ref group=upper-alpha>Intended for "rough weather or novice racers." {{cite web |url=http://www.hartleyboats.com/index.php?id=70&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=202&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=70&cHash=36dc41327bdc7307410d22ab7c0cb7f3 |title=Hartley Wayfarer Mark IV |accessdate=13 November 2013}} Distances and the likelihood of rescue are other factors that should be considered in deciding whether to prepare for the worst.  As [[Franz Kafka]] and [[Huey Lewis and the News]] have written: "It is better to have it and not need it, than need it and not have it."</ref> These include floats (e.g., one that looks like a streamlined [[blimp]] used on [[Hobie 16]]s)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sailsportmarine.com/index.php?main_page=product_info&products_id=277 |title=Hobie Mast Float {{ndash}} Mama Bob |publisher=Sailboat Marine |accessdate= November 17, 2013}}</ref><ref name="forum">{{cite web |url=http://sailingforums.com/threads/faq-what-should-i-do-to-prevent-turtling.26221/ |title=What Should I do to Prevent Turtling |publisher=sailingforums.com |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> or a "sail patch" {{mdash}} a sleeve with built in flotation that fits over the top of the sail, available for example as option on the [[Wayfarer (dinghy)]] Mark IV.  Another alternative is to seal the mast, thereby increasing its [[buoyancy]].<ref name="forum"/> 

As an emergency palliative, putting flotation (''i.e.'', a spare [[life vest]] or other [[personal flotation device]]), onto the end of the mast straight away after a capsize and without delay, can forestall a turtle.  Conversely, climbing onto the side of a knocked down boat can increase the likelihood of turtling, as it moves weight higher over the [[center of gravity]], may also increase windage, and thus can effectively drive the mast downward.<ref name="f15"/>

Several devices have been patented to prevent turtling.<ref name="Legare"/><ref>{{cite patent
