}}</ref> Capsizing is particularly troublesome for [[catamaran]]s and [[trimaran]]s, which are especially hard to right.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/><ref name="Legare">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/patents/US5255624 |title=U.S. Patent No. 5255624 |publisher=Google patents |accessdate=November 17, 2013}} which includes a discussion of turtling. </ref>

==Practice and cure==
Righting a turtled boat is one of the most difficult maneuvers.  Recovery in a monohull requires releasing the [[main sheet]], lowering the [[spinnaker]] if it is deployed, standing on the bottom of the boat and levering on the centerboard, or standing on the centerboard (there may be weight and placement restrictions).  It is important that other members of the crew not be on top the boat, as this can drastically increase resistance to righting the craft.<ref name="f15">{{cite web |url=http://www.fusionboats.com/pdf/FusionRighting.pdf |title=Fusion Capsize Manual |publisher=F-15 dinghy |format=[[PDF]] |accessdate=November 18, 2013}}</ref>  The use of "righting ropes" materially aids the process. Standing on the centerboard and "piggybacking" of crew members can be highly effective to right a turtled dinghy, as it increases both the weight and leverage being applied.  Use of powerboats to aid is problematical, and depending on the technique used {{mdash}} there are several {{mdash}} may or may not succeed.<ref name="Rosmaniere">{{cite web |url=http://offshore.ussailing.org/AssetFactory.aspx?vid=19214 |title=Tests of Sailor Retrieval, Capsize Recovery and Entrapment |first1=John |last1=Rousmaniere |authorlink1=John Rousmaniere |publisher=[[US Sailing]] |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |format=[[PDF]]}}</ref>  See [[Capsize#Training|Capsize]].<ref name="hb"/>

==Multihulls==
[[File:America's Cup, Plymouth - Aleph capsize (3).jpg |thumb|right|Multihull [[Aleph Sailing Team|Aleph]] capsizing during America's Cup trials, Plymouth]]
[[File:Rejsning-af-kaentret-hobie-cat.jpg|250px|thumb|left|Righting a capsized [[Hobie Cat]].]]

In [[yacht]] sailing, [[multihull]]s are deemed to be more prone to turtling than [[keel]]ed monohulls, and there is essentially no way to right them if they overturn.  The juxtaposition of the hulls and sail when turtled {{mdash}} it makes them inherently stable when inverted {{mdash}} makes them especially resistant to righting.<ref name="Rosmaniere"/><ref name="Legare"/>  Consequently, some are built with a turtle emergency [[escape hatch]] beneath the hull. Indeed, some locales require such safety hatches.<ref name="Kelsall"/>  There are, however, those who feel that the likelihood of a capsize of a large multihull is overrated.<ref name="Farrier">{{cite web |url=http://www.f-boat.com/safety/ |title=Multihull Safety |publisher=Farrier Marine |first1=Ian |last1=Farrier |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |format=HTML}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tritonsatsea.blogspot.com/2005/05/never-buy-boat-unless-your-friends.html |title=Don't buy a Catamaran, you'll die!! |date=May 30, 2005 |publisher=Triton Boat Works |first2=Ann Marie Powers |last2=Triton |first1=Robb Kane |last1=Triton |accessdate=November 20, 2013 |format=HTML}}</ref>  There are others who state that a self righting multihull is the answer, along with designing in safety and proper operation.<ref name="Kelsall">{{cite web |url=http://www.kelsall.com/TechnicalArticles/KCSeaworthinessAndSafety.pdf |first1=Derek |last1=Kelsall |publisher=Kellsall Catamarans |title=Catamaran Seaworthiness and Safety |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |format=PDF}}</ref>   A patent has been issued specifically concerning righting of turtled large multihulls.<ref name="Lake"/>  It is intended to avoid the necessity to use divers and special equipment in a recovery.<ref name="Lake">{{cite web |url=http://www.patentstorm.us/patents/4651666/description.html |first1=John A. |last1=Lake |title=Patent 465166 Description, Multi-hull sailboat righter |accessdate=November 20, 2013}}</ref>

It is, however, possible (and often successfully) to right a capsized small multihull, e.g., a [[Beachcat]].  The process begins with positioning ropes so that the crew can get leverage (acting together is key). Righting [[Beachcat|Beach catamaran]]s that are turtled can be extremely difficult.  Loss of sails, rigging, masts and boats can occur.  A singled-handed self rescue can be assisted by carrying a [[garbage bag]] which is filled with water, and thrown over the rescuer's shoulder.<ref name="hb">{{cite web |url=http://www.hobiecat.com/forums/viewtopic.php?t=143 |title=Righting a Hobie cat |accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref>

Even some large multihulls can be righted at sea {{mdash}} it is a long shot {{mdash}} provided that the skipper is well prepared, knows what he is doing, and has appropriate devices, tools, skills and a workable plan.<ref name="Kelsall"/><ref name="Farrier"/>

{{clr}}

==Notable events==

On June 13, 2012, in the trials leading to the [[America's Cup]], [[Oracle Team USA]] on an [[AC45]] spectacularly capsized the boat. and it was righted with minimal damage ("there's a little rip there") ten minutes later.  Skipper [[Russell Coutts]] dismissed it as "a learning experience."  This was an epilogue to earlier similar incidents by other teams in Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-KNql99zT6s |title=America's Cup: Russell Coutts on AC45 Oracle capsizes spectacularly in San Francisco |publisher=[[Sailing News]] |format=video |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sail-world.com/USA/Americas-Cup:-Coutts-capsizes-in-San-Francisco---crew-injured-+-Video/84704 |title=America's Cup: Coutts capsizes in San Francisco - crew injured |format=Video |first1=Richard |last1=Gladwell |publisher=Sail-World.com |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>

On May 9, 2013, the [[2013 America's Cup]] challenger Artemis broke apart, [[Broach (sailing)|broached]]. capsized, and turtled destroying its wing/sail and trapping two crew members under its hull.  The [[AC72]] [[Wingsail|wing-sail]] [[catamaran]] was sailed on behalf of the [[Kungliga Svenska Segels<U+00E4>llskapet|Royal Swedish Yacht Club]] (KSSS), sponsoring [[Team Artemis]]. [[Andrew Simpson (sailor)|Andrew "Bart" Simpson]], an Olympic-gold-medal winning [[United Kingdom|British]] sailor, died as a result.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/09/americas-cup-sailor-dies_n_3248418.html |title=America's Cup Sailor Dies In Boat Capsize |first1=Paul |last1=Elias |first2=Bernie |last2=Wilson |location=San Francisco |date=May 9, 2013 |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |newspaper=[[Huffington Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/video/americas-cup-boat-capsizes-leaving-1-dead-19146864 |title=America's Cup Boat Capsizes, Leaving 1 Dead |newspaper=[[ABC News]] |date=May 9, 2013 |format=video |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>

In one notable crash, the high speed experimental [[sailing hydrofoil]] [[trimaran]] [[Hydropt<U+00E8>re]] set a world speed record, then [[pitchpoled]] while going over 60 knots,  The turtled yacht had to be towed back to port for being turned right side up.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.catsailingnews.com/2008/12/hydroptere-61knots-and-huge-crash-with.html |title=Hydropt<U+00E8>re: 61 knots and huge crash with 35-38 knots, gusts over 45 |publisher=Catamaran Racing |date=December 22, 2008 |location=[[Fos-sur-Mer]] |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>

==Legal implications==
Capsize and turtling can result in legal liability for damages due to [[negligence]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2087529/Girl-11-drowned-gust-wind-capsized-sailing-boat-Greece.html |title=Girl, 11, 'drowned after freak gust of wind capsized catamaran, trapping her underwater in harness' |first1=Andy |last1=Dolan |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |date=17 January 2012 |accessdate=21 November 20123}}</ref>

